<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <%- include('partials/head') %>

  <body>
    <%- include('partials/nav') %>

    <main>
      <section class="food-support-hero">
        <h1>Food Support in Ladywood</h1>
        <p>Understanding the food challenges facing our community and why support matters.</p>
      </section>

        <section class="food-support-cta">
        <h2>Find Food Support Near You</h2>
        <p>Browse food support services available in the Ladywood area.</p>
        <a href="/services?category=Food Support" class="btn-services">View Food Support Services</a>
      </section>

      <section class="food-info">

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Food Insecurity in Ladywood</h2>
          <p>
            High food insecurity means that choices are often based on what is available and cheap,
            such as takeaways or highly processed foods. In Birmingham, 2.3% of adults experience
            hunger due to a lack of food, 11.8% struggle to access food, and 12.4% worry about
            having enough food. In 2022, only half of Birmingham's citizens ate five portions of
            fruit and vegetables per day.
          </p>
          <p>
            High rates of poverty directly influence food insecurity, which can range from
            uncertainty about someone's ability to buy food, to skipping meals or going a day or
            more without food. 15% of UK households experienced food insecurity in January 2024.
            Uncertainty about access to food, and going without food for periods of time, leads to
            stress that can also contribute to wider health problems.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Why Food Support Matters</h2>
          <p>
            Food can bring communities together, supporting good health and mental wellbeing.
            Ladywood is the second most deprived constituency in Birmingham, with 55% of its
            youth living in deprivation — compared to the nationwide average of 30%. The rising
            cost of living has made it much more difficult for many people to afford food.
          </p>
          <p>
            There are almost 100 food banks in the Ladywood Parliamentary Constituency area.
            Food banks use a voucher system to provide food parcels for at least three days for
            free. Vouchers can be accessed through advice services, social services, support
            workers in schools, law centres, GPs and the Citizens Advice Bureau. 7% of Birmingham
            citizens reported using food banks during lockdown in the Birmingham Food Survey.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Food and Climate</h2>
          <p>
            Rising global temperatures are having a profound impact on local and global food
            systems. Many regions on which the UK relies for food will become increasingly
            uninhabitable. More intense weather patterns and less predictable seasons threaten
            food security — in 2020, the UK's wheat production fell by 40% due to increased
            rainfall and drought. This, coupled with rising costs of food production globally,
            will lead to more difficult and more expensive food supplies.
          </p>
          <p>
            Ladywood Parliamentary Constituency has just 5m² of green space per person, and 72%
            of its neighbourhoods have less than 10% tree cover. Growing spaces can be a valuable
            asset to increasing access to culturally important food and growing practices, yet are
            challenged by soil health, access to land, and years of historic industrial activity
            that risks soil quality.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Community Food Growing</h2>
          <p>
            There is a growing movement towards local food growing initiatives aimed at promoting
            healthy access to food and breaking down barriers so people can experience the benefits
            of growing fruit and vegetables. Birmingham has 113 allotment sites and nearly 7,000
            plots — more than any other local authority in the UK. However, the available land
            and fertile soil could only sustain a maximum of 35,000 people in fresh foods in a
            city of over one million.
          </p>
          <p>
            Community organisations across Ladywood are working to address food insecurity.
            Initiatives like Warm Earth, EAT MAKE PLAY, and Incredible Surplus use growing spaces,
            food sharing and community kitchens to connect people, reduce waste and improve
            wellbeing. The Birmingham Food Revolution recognises the need for action by exploring
            and championing those making a difference to the city's food system.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Access to Food in Ladywood</h2>
          <p>
            There are several supermarkets accessible by car, bus and foot in the area. However,
            many are located on one side of the Ladywood middleway, which residents must cross on
            foot to reach. The cost of living crisis has compounded difficulties in affording food,
            with 34% of spending in Birmingham going on foods high in fat, salt and sugar, and on
            takeaways — while fruit and vegetables make up only 11% of food expenditure.
          </p>
          <p>
            Food support services act as a vital safety net and are often a first point of contact
            for people who are struggling. They also connect people with wider support — including
            advice services, mental health support and community networks.
          </p>
        </div>

      </section>

    

    </main>

    <%- include('partials/footer') %>
  </body>
</html>
